In Sprint 1, the main aim of the code was to create the *basic foundation* of the NHS Patient-Centric Hospital System. At this stage, 
the team focused on the three most important features needed for the first working prototype: secure patient login, appointment booking, and viewing medical records. 
These stories were selected because they directly matched the main requirements of the project and gave the team a realistic starting point. 

From the coding side, Sprint 1 was mainly built around the LoginForm, DashboardForm, BookAppointmentForm, and MedicalRecordsForm.
The LoginForm was used as the entry point of the system so that a patient could sign in before accessing any other feature. After successful login, the patient was taken to the DashboardForm,
which acted as the main navigation area of the prototype. From there, the user could move to the appointment booking page or the medical records page.

The BookAppointmentForm in Sprint 1 represented the first version of the online booking feature.
It allowed the patient to choose a doctor, select a date, and choose an available time slot. The MedicalRecordsForm gave the patient access to their own health information in a simple and clear layout. At this stage, the system was still working as a basic prototype, 
using simple in-memory data rather than a full database. The purpose of Sprint 1 was therefore to prove that the main patient journey could work at a basic level before adding more complexity in later sprints.
